projects.title: Sally, customer success oracle (Day 1)
projects.description: Sally lives on ww.willow.co/success-stories too know. Been wanting to implement this for months but never felt confident about how to do it. Since I got more experience with webhooks now, I gave it another shot and it was easier than expected. Starting with a script for Webflow written by ChatGPT, it was easy enough to connect it to n8n and send back replies to the web page.  Styling it was something I could easily do manually as well. Pretty happy with the result. ![[Screenshot 2026-01-29 at 16

projects.title: Sally, customer success oracle (Day 2)
projects.description: Just made a Slack bot that everyone in the team can talk to to ask questions about our successful customers.   But it can also answer other questions like:   - Which customers are in IT?   - Which customers have an office manager?   - Who had the most impressions last year?   How does it work?   Two simple n8n workflows.   1. Every time a new success story gets added (or updated) to Webflow, it gets synced to a database   2. Slack messages get passed on to an AI Agent who only takes the database

projects.title: Wardrobe (Day 2)
projects.description: 1. **Converted desktop app to web app** - Transformed the CustomTkinter desktop wardrobe manager into a Flask-based web application 2. **Unified database** - Merged separate wardrobe.db and wardrobe_fer.db into single database with `wardrobe` field to distinguish owners 3. **Added search & filter** - Implemented debounced search (300ms), type filtering, and sorting by rating/brand/date 4. **Built REST API** - Created 10+ Flask endpoints for CRUD operations, search, filter, sort, and undo functio

projects.title: Newsletter automater
projects.description: Added a timestamp to yaml so I kind of have a feeling which emails I should read first. Also updated the script so it only processes unread emails instead of all emails. Then I ran the script again and I deleted everything from the gmail folders. Hope I didn't miss anything :) Definitely already noticed that I'm much more likely to open the emails from Obsidian than from my email app when I'm looking for something to do while waiting.
